<h2 class="wp-block-heading list-start">Anatomy Of The Inner Chest</h2>



<p>The inner chest<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538321/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow"> muscles</a> generally refer to the muscles surrounding the rib cage. They are classified into two main groups: the pectoralis minor and the pectoralis major. The <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6466946/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">pectoralis major</a> includes three heads: the clavicular, sternocostular, and abdominal head. </p>



<p>Both pectoralis muscle groups attach to the upper arm, actively support respiratory movements, and stabilize the ribs. They also assist the upper arm and shoulder muscles during shoulder movements like lifting, pushing, pulling, and throwing.</p>


